{
  "$schema": "https://aka.ms/codetour-schema",
  "title": "00 — Orientation: the whole project in 5 minutes",
  "description": "Start here. This tour walks the project layout — main.go, migrations, each internal package, and the web layer — before you dive into the detailed concept tours.",
  "steps": [
    {
      "file": "main.go",
      "line": 1,
      "title": "0.1 — What Balaur is",
      "description": "Balaur compiles to **one binary**. Run it with `go run . serve` (development) or build it with `CGO_ENABLED=0 go build -o balaur .` (release). The binary:\n\n- Embeds **PocketBase** as a Go library — a SQLite-backed data/auth engine\n- Serves the **HTMX web UI** from memory (no external server needed)\n- Runs **local LLM inference** through Kronk (llama.cpp loaded at runtime)\n- Can also talk to any **OpenAI-compatible endpoint** (Ollama, llama-server, remote)\n\nThe binary does not contain models — those are downloaded data. But all application code, templates, and CSS are embedded at compile time.\n\nSee `go.mod` for the dependency tree. Notice there's no web framework, no ORM, no router library — PocketBase provides the HTTP router; Go's standard library covers the rest."
    },
    {
      "file": "main.go",
      "line": 16,
      "title": "0.2 — main.go: three lines of wiring",
      "description": "```go\napp := pocketbase.New()\nmigratecmd.MustRegister(app, app.RootCmd, ...)\napp.OnServe().BindFunc(func(se *core.ServeEvent) error {\n    web.Register(se)\n    return se.Next()\n})\napp.Start()\n```\n\n`main.go` is intentionally thin — three concerns:\n\n1. **Create the app** — PocketBase with default SQLite storage\n2. **Register migrations** — the blank import `_ \"balaur/migrations\"` runs `init()` in that package, registering the schema\n3. **Mount routes** — `web.Register(se)` adds the HTMX UI routes after PocketBase's own routes\n\nEverything else lives in focused packages under `internal/`. AGENTS.md rule: *entrypoints stay focused on orchestration; move logic into `lib/*.go`*."
    },
    {
      "file": "migrations/1749600000_init.go",
      "line": 10,
      "title": "0.3 — Schema as code",
      "description": "```go\nfunc init() {\n    m.Register(InitCollections, dropCollections)\n}\n```\n\n`init()` is a special Go function that runs automatically when the package is imported — before `main()`. Here it registers the migration with PocketBase's migration runner.\n\nThe filename prefix `1749600000` is a Unix timestamp — migrations run in filename order (alphabetically), so the timestamp ensures correct sequence as you add more migrations later.\n\n`InitCollections` creates all 7 collections: `conversations`, `messages`, `memories`, `skills`, `heads`, `grants`, `audit_log`. All with owner-only API rules — no anonymous or cross-user access.\n\n**Explore the schema:** open `pb_data/data.db` in any SQLite viewer after running the server once, and browse the `_collections` table."
    },
    {
      "file": "internal/llm/llm.go",
      "line": 41,
      "title": "0.4 — Package map: internal/llm",
      "description": "Balaur's single seam to language models. Two files:\n\n- `llm.go` — the `Client` interface and shared types (`Message`, `Chunk`, `ToolCall`, `ToolSpec`)\n- `kronk.go` — local inference: `KronkClient` loads a GGUF model in-process via Kronk\n- `openai.go` — remote inference: `OpenAIClient` talks to any OpenAI-compatible HTTP endpoint\n\nEverything above this package is provider-agnostic. The `Loop` in `internal/agent` holds a `llm.Client` — it never knows which implementation is running.\n\n**Tour 01** covers this package in depth.\n\nProvider choice is explicit (env vars `BALAUR_CHAT_MODEL` or `BALAUR_REMOTE_URL`). Balaur never auto-routes."
    },
    {
      "file": "internal/agent/agent.go",
      "line": 71,
      "title": "0.5 — Package map: internal/agent",
      "description": "The conversation loop: `messages → model → tool calls → tool results → model …` until the model answers in plain text.\n\n- `agent.go` — `Loop.Run()`, the orchestrator\n- `agent_test.go` — 4 tests with a `fakeClient`, no real model needed\n\nThe loop has no knowledge of PocketBase, HTTP, or the UI. It takes a `llm.Client`, a list of `Tool`s, and an `emit func(Event)` callback — then drives the conversation. The caller decides what to do with events (stream HTML, append to a slice, write to a database).\n\n**Tour 03** covers the loop step by step.\n**Tour 04** covers the tests."
    },
    {
      "file": "internal/heads/heads.go",
      "line": 1,
      "title": "0.6 — Package map: internal/heads",
      "description": "Sub-agent identity and the security boundary.\n\n- `heads.go` — `Spawn`, `Resolve`, `Merge`, `Revoke`: the lifecycle of a head (sub-agent)\n- `scoped.go` — `Scoped`: the **only** sanctioned data path for code acting as a head\n- `heads_test.go` — integration tests proving access denial works and is audited\n\nThe critical invariant: Go-side PocketBase access bypasses API rules. So tool code running as a head must call `AsHead(app, head).Records(...)` — not `app.FindRecordsByFilter(...)`. The `Scoped` type enforces this at the API level.\n\n**Tour 05** covers this in full, including running the security proof test."
    },
    {
      "file": "internal/tools/os.go",
      "line": 1,
      "title": "0.7 — Package map: internal/tools",
      "description": "The four OS access tools: `read`, `write`, `edit`, `bash`.\n\nAll four are **disabled by default**. Set `BALAUR_OS_ACCESS=1` to enable them. Every invocation is written to `audit_log` — both allowed and failed calls.\n\nEach tool is a `agent.Tool` struct with:\n- A `Spec` describing the tool to the model (name, description, JSON Schema for arguments)\n- An `Execute` function literal containing the actual OS operation\n\nThis file is a good place to see function literals, `encoding/json.Unmarshal` for parsing tool arguments, `exec.CommandContext` for running shell commands, and the audit pattern in practice."
    },
    {
      "file": "internal/web/web.go",
      "line": 1,
      "title": "0.8 — Package map: internal/web",
      "description": "The HTMX UI layer.\n\n- `web.go` — `Register()` mounts routes; `handlers` struct holds app + templates\n- `chat.go` — `POST /ui/chat`: receives a user message, streams HTML fragments back\n\nThe UI is server-rendered `html/template` pages. HTMX swaps fragments into the DOM — no JS framework, no build step in the product path. The PocketBase admin dashboard stays at `/_/` for superuser data inspection.\n\nThe `web/` directory at the root holds the embedded assets:\n- `web/static/basm.css` — the canonical design token source (DESIGN.md)\n- `web/static/htmx.min.js` — vendored, no CDN at runtime\n- `web/templates/home.html` — the single-page shell\n- `web/embed.go` — exposes the `embed.FS` so the binary includes them"
    },
    {
      "file": "internal/search/fts5_test.go",
      "line": 1,
      "title": "0.9 — Package map: internal/search (spike)",
      "description": "This package currently contains one thing: a **spike test** that proves FTS5 full-text search works under the `ncruces/go-sqlite3` driver.\n\nPocketBase's default driver (`modernc.org/sqlite`) does **not** ship with FTS5. The `ncruces` driver is WASM-based, CGO-free, and includes FTS5. When vault recall lands, the driver will be wired into PocketBase's `DBConnect` config (officially documented — Tour 01 step 1.7 mentions the pattern).\n\nUntil then, it's a test-only dependency that adds nothing to the binary. The test documents the decision and protects against regressions if the driver changes.\n\n**Run it:**\n```\ngo test ./internal/search/ -v\n```"
    }
  ]
}